Is there a black box in your car?
While U.S. road designers are trying to find the money to repair the crumbling road system, many begin to see the solution in a small black box neatly mounted on the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile driven by a motorist and pass this information on to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by planning authorities in Washington and the state.
Usually, the boring arena of highway planning suddenly gave rise to intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even possibly where you drive them — and then use that information when drawing up tax bills.
The tea-drinking movement is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of privacy issues.
And although Congress cannot agree on whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They are thinking about how the next decade could see a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of drivers have already taken to testing these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“This is not an issue that we can have the right to choose from,” said Hasan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state’s miles traveled by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
The technology for that already exists.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government Fund for the construction of highways, financed by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax by even one cent at high prices for gasoline.
“It’s simply impossible to keep a tax on gasoline,” said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices have recently been installed on cars to test the erroneous payment system.
“It will be the best alternative in the long term,” he said.
Boredom calls this the wrong user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, since with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce the congestion of roads and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are looking into this system in the process of developing strategies to achieve the targets set by that state's ambitious global warming laws.
However, House Representative Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also views the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market supporters at the Reason Fund are also thrilled that drivers will be forced to pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that’s going to go into the black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s vice president of political affairs.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move in the direction of wrongful payment.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would involve about 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural legislators representing voters, who in everyday life often have to travel many miles to get to work or to the city.
A few states and cities, however, go this route on their own.
The biggest enthusiasm is in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for mileage instead of the gas tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
In New York, it is under consideration.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of the 17 eastern states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how they can make these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 vehicles of volunteers were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track every step of the way.
“Concerns about the big brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
As the tests went on, the American Civil Liberties Union office in Nevada warned on its website: “It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure, which will inevitably be expanded to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states where the search for a low-cost technology that would allow the state authorities to keep track of miles traveled by car, but without information about the location and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not involved in helping to collect state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of the type of auto insurance, in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically loaded via a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There were some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less obsessive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can completely abandon the device, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state pass.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to the cautious public, forcing the devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxing device that will also accept parking meters, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect a real-time speed data pool from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists will be attracted to the participation of the benefits that will be offered to them,” the city planning document says.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering whether not all talk of mispayment is just a huge distraction.
In the city’s San Francisco Bay Area Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Trust Fund for Highway Construction by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on drivers of hybrid vehicles and other persons whose vehicles do not use much gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the law and public relations commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of the EU-Ukraine Association Agreement at the Vilnius Summit.
The IMF is negotiating a stand-by loan, and another EU official, directly involved in the negotiations, added that their goal is to conclude an agreement in the near future.
In addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts interviewed by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are capable of overcoming long-standing disagreements on funding conditions.
Does not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to obtain assistance, and the international rating agency S&P, which lowered on Friday the sovereign rating of Ukraine by one degree - to "B-" with "B".
However, EU representatives say that the IMF can show flexibility in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the country’s financial support plan, the EU has a backup option to provide Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of which is now coming from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from the "North Stream" or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way in the event that Russia "isolates" Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reversible deliveries to Ukraine can only be used for a few weeks, and is likely to lead to a decrease in deliveries to other regions.
"Negotiations are underway between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but on other routes," the source added.
Russia out of the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most of the world's megacities since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their redevelopment and expansion of the highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
There is a well-known example of Singapore, where a strict quota for the increase in the number of private cars is introduced, and the right to purchase them is bought at auction.
Its price can be two or three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entering the city centre.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where entry is allowed only for cars with a certain eco-class, which also use high-quality fuels (including biofuels or electric vehicles).
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 a "five-year clean air plan" with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to the director of the transport pollution control department of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, Li Kunsheng, the main goal of the five-year - to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, the increase in the number of private cars increased to a level of not more than 6 million (now also 5.2 million).
According to the agency, car transport in Beijing is now responsible for 22.5% of the total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program are the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year" include the development of the urban transport accelerated compared to the rest of the country, the transition to the European fuel standards, the introduction of the local system of eco-standards and the marking of cars and fuel, the restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, the prohibition on the use of outdated vehicles.
The number of car innovations of Beijing also includes a ban for all private cars on traffic within the fifth transport ring (in total in the capital of the People's Republic of China there are six) one day a week (corresponding information is contained in the registration number of the vehicle), as well as the issue of registration plates for cars on the basis of the lottery.
According to the current state program "Environmental Protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011 the “mobile sources” accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial ones, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In the Russian Federation, they are just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy of the Higher Education Institution, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips are unpopular, they can only be adopted by society if they are fully universal.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem related to the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory impacts - commercial and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200,000 (about 5% of the total number of cars in Moscow).
Recently, urban planners from the ECOM Center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the amount of road transport.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice as much as required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking lots, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the road section (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the city's security zone of the historic center (a total area of about 3212 square meters).
