Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks for Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments for unsecured consumer loans and massive employee cuts.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather, the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is completely driven by consumption, which almost does not slow down the turnover," said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs in Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation at 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at roughly the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so it is likely that they will optimize personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages increase by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
The companies were faced with a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to redundancies and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business cannot not raise wages, comments the chief economist of Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment close to historical minimums, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees away or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is booming and very rapid growth in consumer credit.
According to Mr. Graf, due to the extremely high rates of consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not diverge in the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is another - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in default on unsecured loans.
They are mainly taken by poor people, who have nothing to provide.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often," said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of defaults on unsecured loans.
The Director of the Banking Institute of VSE Vasily Solodkov already sees signs of a maturing banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, without access to the cheap resources of the state banks, were forced to attract public funds at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to lower credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not abandon dumping, Russia is threatened by a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a forerunner of a mass collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with such a situation: the deposit insurance system was initially not designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the failure to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, enshrined in the current version of the draft budget.
In part, the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, by lowering inflation).
But only in part: if the investment does not grow (and the prerequisites for this are not yet - see the reference), the growth of consumption will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still a fall in the price of oil,” he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink with the price of oil below $ 90 / bar.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet in a position to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has fallen and banks have started to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,” said Clemens Grafe.
The Central Bank’s interest rate policy does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes," Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank is not used by banks to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity.
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will realize that this strategy is not working,” Grafe said, recalling that the state plans to release the ruble into “free navigation” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do this earlier, or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the rate of the ruble is now artificially exaggerated by 10%.
Ruble only one way - to weaken, - concludes the expert.
But if the Central Bank plunges into the financiers at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy of weakening the ruble, it may collapse the ruble much more strongly.
