Snowden is ready to “cooperate” with Germany on the issue of U.S. intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence officer, said he was ready to go to Berlin to give testimony to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, were unable to answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr. Snowden, which the deputy presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: "Although the result of my efforts was clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal defenses that do not give any.
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In a letter, Mr. Snowden said he believes support from the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make this possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have become tense after allegations that the NSA had tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a member of parliament who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said that if there is a possibility to listen to Mr. Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him or completely destroying relations with the United States,” it should be used.
Mr. Ströbele, a member of parliament from Germany’s Green Party, posted his photo with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that, according to a lawyer for a former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not have returned to Russia if he had left.
If Mr. Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need guarantees that he would be “safe” there, the MP said.
Mr Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and constant” persecution campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the global response to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials — including in the United States — have found the disclosure of an uncontrolled system of pervasive surveillance to be beneficial to society.
The letter proposes to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved.”
Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to leave the entire bank.
The new fee for hand luggage applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free of charge.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would only pay at the landing gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 fee should make passengers pay in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for it,” she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second bags, which were left in their luggage, in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges pack as much as they can in the hand luggage compartment, which is why these compartments often do not have enough space.
Fees are one way to make passengers carry less on board.
O'Malley said this new collection isn't really about making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that finding a place in the upper luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the exit of the Frontier flight may be able to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue may pay $100 for the same bag.
O'Malley said the change in procedures on the website and at Frontier's check-in counters was meant to ensure that passengers would be aware of the charge before they land.
The new Frontier manual deposit fee will not start charging until summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that the handling of luggage is worth the money, and passengers who need this service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges a sign that airlines charge enough money to cover the cost of air travel after several years of losses.
However, most of them did not cover the fees for manual storage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first handbag charge three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
According to his estimate in the December 2011 report, the collection for manual deposits brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines top manager, recently flew a Spirit flight, and he was wondering what he would find at the landing gate when passengers encounter an unusual Spirit collection for hand luggage.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my career with airlines,” he said.
I was expecting to see a toothbrush and a fight at the landing gate.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit in terms of a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda, or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive soda or juice can leave a whole can and that coffee beans will be provided free of charge.
It will continue to distribute water for free.
US Airways tried to charge for drinks for a short time in 2008, but declined to do so seven months later, after passengers began to complain and no other major airline followed suit.
The Frontier initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest move to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers, such as Orbitz, between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier went further in this area.
In September, she began giving twice as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent from miles of travel.
For example, a 1000-mile trip from Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue fell by 9 percent, and flight opportunities fell by almost 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix Frontier’s finances as part of the airline’s sale.
NSA blames “internal error” and not hackers in the termination of the site
The National Security Agency said on Friday night that shutting down their website for several hours had caused a technical failure, not hackers, according to the network.
"NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during the scheduled update," the agency said in a statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Statements that the work interruption was caused by a distributed denial-of-service attack [DDoS] are incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems reported that the NSA’s website hadn’t worked for at least six hours, and the site was still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, the NSA representative told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network “nothing” was hacked.
No classified information is in jeopardy, the representative said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for shutting down the NSA’s website via a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to engulf the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
The tactics of hackers are relatively simple, and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
Previously, the super-secret NSA, once nicknamed "No Such Agency", has been in the center of public attention and harsh criticism in recent months after a series of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and inside the country.
The growing controversy around the agency has sparked speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
Bombardier’s profit declines with falling deliveries and number of aircraft orders
Bombardier, a Canadian manufacturer of planes and trains, said on Thursday it had cut net profits by 15 per cent under the impact of declining orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contract problems in its rail division.
The Montreal-based Bombardier company also did not release any flight test data for its latest CSeries aircraft and did not provide new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial service by next September will be implemented.
After the first flight of an experimental aircraft, which took place about one and a half months ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results did not meet the forecasts and led to a decline of more than 8 percent in shares on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, on Thursday lowered his valuation from “higher-than-average” to “middle-market” due to the belief that stock growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed by the transport department’s earnings figures,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to gain a place in the lower price segment of the market, where Boeing and Airbus now dominate.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and made its first flight in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries are not yet too many – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for flight test results to verify the company’s claims about the fuel efficiency and potential cost-effectiveness of the new liner.
Currently, there are 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would achieve its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial service.
On Thursday, the leaders also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Bodouan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the aircraft's downtime.
All manufacturers plan tests in different ways.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all the rest will soon follow, the company said.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is assessing the timing of commissioning and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing — albeit apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule — reinforces our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ending September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same – 9 cents.
Gross income declined slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected a 10-cent profit per share and gross income of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft per quarter, down from 57 in the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The portfolio of orders of the aerospace department amounted to $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and general market conditions have become an unpleasant factor,” said Bodouan.
Gross revenue in the aerospace direction fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure of December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were negatively affected by the problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management said a new development plan would be presented in the fourth quarter.
The shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pitchett would join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to $4.83 at a mid-Thursday trade.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest competitor, said on Thursday it had cut quarterly revenue by 10 percent.
Sony expects lower annual earnings
The Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony Corporation, ended the past quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, cut its forecast for profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s July-September 2013 results were more depressing than expected due to the drop in demand for televisions, camcorders and personal computers manufactured by the Japanese corporation.
Sony’s television business, which brought the company its first operating profit in three years of 5.2 billion yen, fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operating loss in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is experiencing difficult times, especially due to the declining demand for televisions.
