The gene of speech proved to be a stimulant of the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the Foxp2 gene performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce the words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
Scientists found that family members had been disrupted by the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function was not known.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least some of their functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the area of the brain associated with the formation of speech.
It does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 proved to be one of the 10 similar genes found by the authors, with Foxp2 only blaming for its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, the scientists confirmed in the experiment on mice.
When the animals had artificially reduced gene activity, they screamed less when shared with the mother.
If the gene activity was restored, the frequency of the emitted sounds was also restored.
Previously, mice also showed a connection with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were injected with a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 managed by it is related to purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or to more subtle processes.
