For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government troops and Renamo — one of the most brutal clashes since the truce was signed more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known rebel movement, which was supported first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 truce, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to revert to a full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge shelves of gas and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
The ruling Frelimo Party, the leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo Party blame each other for the tensions.
The Renamo party claims that the government has been the source of the latest clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofia, the traditional Renamo stronghold, on October 17.
The attacks on former rebels then escalated as government troops attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakamu, the group’s leader, Renamo’s spokesman Fernando Mazanga told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Gebuza tried to dispel concerns about the instability.
Gebuza told AFP on Wednesday that Mr. Dhlakama felt “a failure” to use “everything left of his power to try to prove that he can impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, concerns grew after Mazanga announced that Renamo had renounced the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he meant non-compliance by the Frelimo party.
“Our goal is to return to the negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous negotiations between the parties have done little to ease the tensions that have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) who have come face-to-face,” said Joseph Hanlon, an Open University lecturer and expert on Mozambique.
Neither of them is a good negotiator and neither of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
The Renamo party, which is trying to achieve electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
The presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to obtain concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was founded by a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in these elections.
Mr. Mazanga says that Mr. Gebuza, who is due to resign next year, when his second term ends, wants to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is not clear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key highway leading from north to south.
Most of the clashes took place in the province of Sofia, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beirut, a port that mining companies, including Rio Tinto and Vale, use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of the railways for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
The Renamo party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going very well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
The instability has heightened government dissatisfaction, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and recent kidnappings, said Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who must find a solution to these problems,” he said.
Omar Sultan, a participant in the demonstration, said that people just want stability.
“Nobody cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want to restore peace, they want free access to roads,” he said.
