Energy companies of Dnipropetrovsk have started a unique program to save... nests of aisles
In antiquity, to bring to the court of the Aistos, the peasants on the high pillar installed a wheel from the wagon, and the heavy nest was well held on it.
Such special supports have not been put in place for a long time, so the aists loved the pillars of the power lines - the intertwined branches rest on the wires, thanks to which the real house stands securely.
Grandmother Anya, whose real family has lived in the village of Ivanovka in the Petrikovsky district for twenty years, began to notice how the nest settles, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
The birds put new branches on top, and the lower layer has already passed between the wires, it is about to collapse.
Of course, it is a pity that the family of aesthetes, who each year nested in the yard, raised and fed three or four chicks during the summer, but also without the light do not want to remain without it.
As soon as the birds flew to the warm areas, Grandma Anja called the Tsarichan Reservoir, which owns the support.
I didn’t expect them to react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest is still holding at all, - said the technical director of DTEK "Dneprooblenergo" Sergei Berezovsky.
On the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150 - 200 kilograms, corrosion began.
At any moment, the birds could die from electric shock.
And the locals risked to run out of light because of the damage to the wires.
Therefore, the linear mounters started the operation to rescue the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Scientists-ornithologists from Dnipropetrovsk National University, who developed a scheme for the transfer of the nest, helped.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
Famous Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised energy engineers at all stages of the reconstruction of the nests.
For the first time, it was estimated that there are more than 50 real "apartments" in the area in an emergency.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms resembling a funnel were welded.
The base was weaved with spruce branches, and then transferred there the old nest.
According to experts, it is enough to lay the old branches as a basis for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
Afterwards, the Aistahs build their own houses.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka in the Novomoskovsky district.
Next to the electrical support was placed a new concrete pillar and placed on it a platform with an old, already inhabited nest.
The entire operation cost the energy engineers nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day, the same settlement took place in the village of Ivanovka in the Petrikovsky district in the courtyard of Grandma Ani.
Here the platform was fixed in the same place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their "apartment" has undergone major repairs.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction awaits four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichan districts of Dnipropetrovsk.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
The other day, the whole region flew with a sad news - in the village of Ust-Kamenka of the Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the pheasant hunt, poachers shot a swan family, who lived on the local pond, for entertainment.
The noble birds were not at all afraid of people - the locals fed them and did not offend them.
When the villagers heard the shots, they ran to the pond, four beautiful swans were already lying dead on the water.
Now the officers of the Apostolov district police department find out who shot the birds listed in the Red Book.
The Russian March is becoming more popular.
On November 4, the Day of National Unity, in Moscow will be held agreed with the city hall "Russian March".
According to a survey of the Levada Center, support for the Russian Marches is growing - already 40% of citizens in varying degrees approve of the idea of holding them.
According to the Levada Center, 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the holding of Russian marches: 11% of them are definitely positive and 29% - "rather positive".
The popularity of the idea of "Russian marches" is gradually growing - in 2006, these actions were welcomed by only 14% of Russians, and in December 2010 the holding of such events has already supported twice as many citizens (28%).
"Definitely negative" to "Russian Marches" belong only 7% of Russians, "rather negative" - 19%.
Another 35% could not formulate their attitude to this action.
This year, the Moscow City Hall agreed to hold a Russian March of up to 15,000 people in Lublin, the head of the security department of the capital, Alexey Majorov, said today.
This nationalist campaign has been held every year since 2005 on the Day of National Unity.
When asked by sociologists “Did you hear that on November 4 in Russia “Russian Marches” are held under the slogans of protection of Russian rights in Russia?” three quarters (75%) of citizens answered negatively.
Currently, only one in five Russians knows about this action (20%).
It is noteworthy that in December 2010 almost a third of citizens (31%) heard about the "Russian Marches".
Recall that three years ago, on December 11 in Manezh Square, a spontaneous rally of nationalists took place, which turned into mass riots.
The Levada Center also asked the Russians about what holiday is celebrated on November 4.
In two years, the number of those who know the correct answer (People’s Unity Day) increased from 41% to 49%.
However, only 15% of citizens are going to celebrate this holiday.
About the same (17%) intend to celebrate the Day of the October Revolution on November 7.
The majority of citizens (62%) are not going to celebrate any of these holidays.
