On the Day of National Unity in 2012, the nationalists marched from Yakimanskaya promenade to the Central House of the artist, where the rally took place.
The organizers estimated the number of participants in 20 thousand people, the Ministry of Internal Affairs called the number 6 thousand.
Message: Obama's Pre-Election Staff Considered Biden's Exclusion in Favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, Obama’s closest advisers were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton in the 2012 electoral roll.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of all the expected book by Mark Halperin and John Hillemann about the 2012 campaign "The stakes have doubled: The game has changed in 2012".
The Times received a copy of the upcoming book and reported on Thursday night that the president's closest aides had conducted "scale focus group research and public opinion polls at the end of 2011" to assess whether Biden's exclusion could help raise staggering hopes for re-election.
According to the political reviewer of The Times Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempt of high-ranking officials of the pre-election headquarters and the White House, namely the former head of the administration of the White House Bill Daley, to assess the effect of the election of the former president.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded in the Chicago pre-election headquarters and in the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former Obama election chief of staff Jim Messin, and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book "Double the stakes" claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden, despite their "close personal relationship", but eventually renounced that step when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral roll would not "significantly improve the odds."
In an interview with Martin Daley, he confirmed that the administration was really considering replacing Biden Clinton.
“I’ve been actively advocating for a lot of things, and it was one of them,” Daley told the paper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, "Oh my God, what are we supposed to do?"
Although Daley described the study as a “necessary check,” Martin told CNN’s Anderson Cooper that the election staff had invested enough in studying whether this move would bring dividends to the vote.
“Pre-election staffs don’t spend that amount of money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously,” Martin said in the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was studying the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then-boss knew about the possible re-draw.
Although Daley said he didn’t think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former head of the administration admitted that “maybe” Obama knew.
Martin added that “The stakes are doubled” does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probe have come to the table of Obama.
Cooper asked Martin if he was serious about Obama not knowing about the possibility of excluding Biden from the electoral roll.
“Perhaps,” Martin said.
