George Kerevan: the gap with Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another scarecrow about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European free movement zone as a condition of EU membership.
There is a series of stories about passport control in Berwick and the border with barbed wire along the Adrianov shaft.
True, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of more free movement across the rest of Europe, although — predictably — this did not appear in the headlines.
No one has also pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time turning their formal rules around as they see fit.
Since Scotland is now not part of the Schengen area, continuing non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in exchange for what it really wanted from the Scots.
So this is not a worthy story.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: for the first time I heard a duck say that “independence means passport control” at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment, lost in the retelling of an ancient fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey Europe’s orders?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the Euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining momentum.
Even in Germany, the “Alternative for Germany” Eurosceptic party – founded only this year – emerged out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in the September federal election, effectively ejecting the “Free Democrats” (an analogue of our “Liberal Democrats”) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures put in place by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are working with excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the euro system has blocked its members at exchange rates that benefit German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is in a pre-disadvantaged position in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only way out is to cut wages and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of budget and currency lies a deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacity.
As a result of the set of measures on “green” energy implemented by Brussels, a code that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the US.
This is paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
No freezing of wages in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, the rebellion, especially in France, once the EU’s most fervent supporter, is ripe.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s devastated economy in a dire situation.
The result is the right-wing anti-EU party Marine Le Pen’s “National Front” has just won crucial by-elections, putting the ruling Socialist Party in third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote — a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split between the right and the left will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties get support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: the soon-to-be-growing sentiments against the EU and against the single currency in Europe are coming together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of a vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies can keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project in the hope of getting closer to the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
What is the situation with Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (in essence) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed under a more free European arrangement, provided that we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and maintaining our economic independence.
The Government of the Scottish National Party in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority of votes in 2011 thanks to objections against the cost reductions proposed (and implemented) by the Labour Chancellor of the Treasury.
It would be absurd for Scotland to vote for independence only to take the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Aging earlier
African-American and Latin American girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that sexual maturation is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early sexual maturity is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children’s health and family issues.
Should a mother be afraid if her daughter begins to form breasts and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — usually it doesn’t mean a quick onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of the book “Early puberty in girls: how to cope with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how sexual maturation will progress.
There is a discussion about what constitutes the actual onset of sexual maturity, but is considered “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression may serve as the basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is wary of medications, but admits that “suppression of puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and the feeling of girls that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or even how they handle hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruation at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we were talking about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones are to blame in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media.
In boys, as in girls, sexual maturation occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the prerequisite that has the greatest weight is an obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped carry out a study of girls between the ages of 6 and 9, which links the amount of fat in the body with the timing of puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African American and Latin American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations.
Around the world, early sexual maturation appears to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although the hair on the face and on the shank of boys appears at a younger age, the tendency to complete early sexual maturation is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors participating in the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of infancy.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of sexual maturity,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be ashamed to receive instructions from the pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean earlier than expected conversation,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier than usual, this process is a normal part of life.
