Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take a few years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Wells Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a strategy of using the vaccine can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying out all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine shot.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activity.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine “relaxed,” and this is a sign that nicotine reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
The previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies to the virus.
To maintain high levels of antibodies, the injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of a new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get pleasure from this because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
