Rules for the use of electronic devices on aircraft in Australia will remain in force for the time being
Passengers of Australian airlines will need to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite measures in the US to mitigate the rules concerning these devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has allowed U.S. carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during take-off and landing, provided they remain in “flight mode.”
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but many are irritated that they do not have access to their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are considering this decision, which required US airlines to spend a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but have indicated that they do not plan to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Office also noted that it is considering the statement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in the critical phases of flight are still in place in Australia.
“The Civil Aviation Safety Administration currently has no specific rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft,” it said.
This issue is governed by rules that require air carriers to ensure safety at all times, and passengers to comply with safety rules, which are communicated to them by crew members.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Safety Board the expansion of its on-board entertainment system with Wi-Fi, was not opposed to the changes, but said it would follow the regulator’s instructions.
“We would welcome the Civil Aviation Safety Board’s consideration of allowing the use of electronic devices because we really think it will improve the quality of customer service now that it (the onboard wireless entertainment system) is on our planes,” the spokesman said.
Qantas has said it will abide by the rules in force at the moment.
“Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and we do not plan to change it in the near future,” she said.
The FAU regulation applies to U.S. airlines.
However, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly carefully study the FAU’s decision and the reasons behind it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the ruling will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their aircraft is resistant to radio waves from mobile devices, as well as review manuals, training materials, rules for carrying hand luggage and instructions for passengers.
“Once the airline checks and confirms the interference resistance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-books and smartphones, at any height,” the FAU said.
