The pawnshop owners in Singapore are doing well, while the middle class is experiencing difficulties
In a pawnshop in Singapore’s Bendemir shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga puts on a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family’s monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is growing — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its transaction, this week became the third pawnbroker listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A jewellery loan is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in Mrs. Amirthaling’s case), but almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
In Singapore, pawnbrokers typically charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% — just above the 15.4% offered by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require credit checks or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
That’s why millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressured by rising cost of living and the rapid growth of household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and cheap loans fuelled by free monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to offset a decline in income savings as their growth slows.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, indicated an increase in family credit leverage, largely due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia led the list with 80% of GDP compared to 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued decline in exports and a weakening of consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that as prices rise, people in the middle and bottom [income range] will be looking for ways to replenish their income wherever they can,” said Song Seng Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record-high gold prices over the past two years have intensified the rush with which people put their personal belongings on, as they take advantage of the opportunity to get money for their family jewellery.
In Singapore, about 70 per cent of the goods deposited at 200 city-state pawnshops are gold.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, let’s put on Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen an increase in the number of customers using its office in recent months, up to 20%.
Growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, a branch operator in Bendemir and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Li Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will finance the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the placement of shares on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have sparked criticism because of high interest rates, Ms Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also does not increase debt directly.
“Customers are putting up items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn’t increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasing public recognition as a means to obtain short-term, secured financing.
And at the same time, pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax offices, laying gold bars or Rolex watches, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for short-term commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” says Ms Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
