the deadline of 1 November set by the Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or “disable” all means of chemical weapons production and mechanisms for mixing chemicals with poisonous gas and filling them with munitions.
The completion of what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious schedule that aims to destroy all of Damascus’ chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nevertheless, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and nerve gas sarin.
The statement was made during fierce fighting Thursday in the city of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons facility as well as its storage location, the UK-based Syrian Centre for Human Rights said.
A group of activists who tracked the losses through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120,296 people were killed.
Of this number, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
The government said 29,954 people are members of President Bashar al-Assad’s armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government militants and 187 are Lebanese Hezbollah militants.
Also among the dead, the statement said, were 2,202 army defectors and about 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to the UN estimate of 25 July, 100,000 people have died in the conflict since March 2011.
Since then, this figure has not been updated.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops fought in Safira for weeks with rebels, many of whom are affiliated with al-Qaeda groups.
The center said on Thursday there were casualties on both sides, but did not provide specific data.
The battles underlined the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, adjusted for the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of a toxic arsenal in the midst of an ongoing civil war.
The OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, said its team was “now satisfied that it has checked and destroyed all of Syria’s declared critical production facilities and mixing/refueling equipment.”
She added that “no additional inspection activities are currently being planned.”
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work by visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
They were unable to visit the two sites for security reasons, the inspectors said.
