FAU: “Air passengers can now use gadgets on airplanes (but not to call from a mobile phone)”
Air passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not to talk on mobile phones, according to long-awaited new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
However, passengers should not expect changes to occur immediately.
How quickly such a change is implemented will vary depending on the airline, FAU administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to show the FAU how their planes meet the new guidelines and that they are updating their flight crew training manuals and device laying rules to comply with the new guidelines.
The FAU said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that have already presented their plans.
“Depending on the status of the plan, we could approve the expansion of the use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAU said.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft door closes.
They should not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain does not give "good".
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the aircraft is lowered for landing, and not turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and flight, the FAU said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Guides, welcomed these changes.
“Once the new policy is successfully implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this) it will be a win-win option,” Glading said.
We are frankly tired of feeling “duty at school” when it comes to this issue.
But Internet access for surfing, sharing emails, text messages or uploading data will still be banned at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, still no "Words with Friends" - an intelligent online game, in which the actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a rumored case: the actor was removed from the aircraft of the airline American Airlines for refusing to turn off the device at the time when the plane.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stored in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones in flight will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls belongs to the Federal Communications Commission, not to the FAU.
FAU may lift ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know from the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
A sectoral advisory committee set up by the FAU to study the issue recommended last month that the government allow more widespread use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been an increase in pressure on FAUs to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no compelling security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radio receivers — high-tech gadgets of the time.
New airliners are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by the FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years now.
Airplanes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners have been adapted for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But the signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was the company Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded an entire airliner with their Kindle e-book reader devices and flew on it to check for problems, but never detected them.
Members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passengers Association said he believes interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only individual pilots' messages confirming that the devices could create interference for aviation systems, and most of these messages are very old.
