Scientists have shed light on how the dog’s tail movements are related to her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs curl their tails to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs curl their tails mostly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family may notice these subtle differences in tail swinging and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that people on the left and right sides of the brain participate differently in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs have the right side of the brain that controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the versatile intrusions of other dogs’ tails, the researchers observed the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We’ll probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point to one side, and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, “We showed dogs videos with dogs — either naturalistic versions or silhouettes to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and point the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that the otherwise expressive dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail leaned mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog waving its tail), their heartbeat increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should worry about and which ones they should not.
He notes: “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs, and often their tail tilting to one side is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these results can give owners, veterinarians, and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, an invited research fellow at the University of Bristol’s veterinary school, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides are relevant to dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a contented dog.
And in another scientific paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the weaning of its tail was directed to the left, rather than to the right, instead of becoming alarmed, is the opposite behavior toward the Italians.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is enough evidence across different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails sometimes point to one side and sometimes to the other.
