Pope Francis will name the first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals to the Catholic Church for the first time in his term of office on February 22, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
The cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the pope, so Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after reaching the age of 80, the cardinal can no longer participate in the election of the pope - this is the prerogative of the group of 120 "electoral cardinals".
Announcing the news, Vatican spokesman Father Federico Lombardi said that a meeting of all current cardinals, known as the Consistory, would be held before the erection ceremony.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene a Consistory in February in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings with the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal electors is likely to decline by February.
He said that the pope usually calls as many cardinals as necessary to bring back the number of cardinals-elections to 120, as well as as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wants.
The Consistory next year will be of great importance because it will be the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a kind of bias in favour of Europe and especially in favour of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see whether the new Pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance,” he said.
In South America, forty percent of Catholics live, but they are represented by a small number of cardinals.
They will also be the first cardinals to be elected since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the church.
In the past, Dad decided everything on his own.
“Now Francis has chosen eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said that “it is quite possible” that Francis would turn to the cardinals for advice.
But we haven’t been in this situation before — it’s all for us for the first time.
Valero said that the popes were usually appointed as cardinal bishops from major parishes, but Francis was “a pool of surprises – so we don’t know who he would call.”
