Egypt's first freely elected president takes oath
Mohammed Mursi takes the oath, but the day of his triumph is unlikely to mark the end of the political struggle in Egypt.
Islamist Mohammad Mursi promised a “new Egypt” when he took the oath of office, becoming the country’s first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was overthrown 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 black-robed judges in a court building on the banks of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are striving for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” Mursi said during a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations of a new life – absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old American-educated engineer from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been a banned organization for most of the 84 years of its existence.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and police when Mursi arrived with a small coach shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered at the courthouse to welcome the new president, and unlike the presidential pump of Mubarak’s time, the movement was halted only for a short time to miss his car-column on the usually busy road connecting the city center with the southern suburbs.
Although Morsi was ridiculed as an uncharismatic “spare wheel” by the Brotherhood, his personal prestige has risen sharply since his victory and Friday speech, in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only of the Islamists, but also of all those who want to bring to an end the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mubarak.
“Egypt today is a civic, national, constitutional and modern state,” Mursi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red tie, told judges in a wooden paneled courtroom where he took the oath.
Morsi later went to the University of Cairo, where he was to deliver his inaugural speech.
He was given an official reception with the army orchestra, which performed the national anthem, during which he stood on the stand "peacefully".
Field Marshal Hussein Tantavi was present.
His arrival was greeted by the slogan "Army and the people - one hand", which chanted hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Founded in 1908 as a fort of secular education, Cairo University in the 1970s became a fort of Islamist student groups.
Mursi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, where an uprising erupted that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and vowed to return the president’s powers, which were deprived of his office by a military council that took cases from the overthrown leader.
But by agreeing to take an official oath before the court, and not before the parliament, as is customary, he is doing the will of the military, and this is a sign that the struggle for power will continue.
Mursi’s speech at Tahrir Square was filled with theatrical populist gestures.
