A trip through the mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking in hundreds of patients
There aren’t that many doctors in this West African country — just one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of CNN’s Top 10 Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and relapse into unconsciousness, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwell had accompanied his father for years in crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwell said.
“You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation has not changed much since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would not be in their pockets.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending in this country is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwell said.
And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwell was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwell and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people pack in vans, tie medical supplies to roofs, and drive across the intersecting area to visit the village in need of help.
They are not always lucky.
Many times they had to push cars across rivers and dirt.
But when they come, they are greeted as true heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed an occasion for celebration, and Bwelle with his broad smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on each trip,” Bwell said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these clinics on weekends provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get ribs, donated glasses, or free birth certificates—documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school building, municipality or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative zone to make room for the next person.
Using the generator to illuminate the operational and sanitary treatment of the equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s an unbearable pace, but the brigade’s determination usually helps to support village musicians.
“They’ve been drumming all night so we can stay awake and keep working,” Bwell said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade return to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free surgery he received to treat the hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical treatments on the weekends and working in the hospital, surgeon Bwelle also works at night in private medical clinics around Yaounde.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bwell group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley, coming from the US and Europe to join Bwell in fulfilling his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice that they would never get at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never have had such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But when they arrive in Yaounde, their food, transportation and training are paid by Bwell.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling their father’s promise, is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy doing this job,” Bwell said.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do to help.
