Rosbalt Agency deprived of the status of media for indecent fighting
On October 31, the Moscow court decided to invalidate the license for the registration of the Rosbalt agency.
The deprivation of the media agency's status insisted Roskomnadzor - for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, de facto denying the publication the right to present counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
ZAO "Information Agency Rosbalt" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has representations in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the publication's proximity to the force structures continued throughout the agency's existence.
In addition to the fact that "Rosbalt" had an extensive base of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions said that at the head of the project was Natalia Chaplina - the wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, the role of Chaplina in the Rosbalt leadership is not clear to the end: she is most often called the "project manager".
The general director of the agency is Larissa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of visits of Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of rosbalt.ru site is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are remarks about the helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Shot", pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
Rosbalt’s conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when an amendment to the media law came into force that banned journalists from engaging in indecent campaigns.
The agency found a banned lexicon in two videos published on the agency's website ("Gigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot defiled the oil towers").
Further sides are described in different ways.
Roskomnadzor accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to withdraw the license from the agency.
Rosbalt claimed that the claims of the agency were wrong: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were masked, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor's claims in the court of peace - and when on October 22, 2013, the Moscow court accepted Roskomnadzor's claim, the examination of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th the world judge made a decision not in favor of "Rosbalt": the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this pre-determined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow court - if you give up the thought that the outcome could have been predicted even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, de facto depriving the agency of the status of media.
It cannot be said that "Rosbalt" remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (a statement to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 signed 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the KPRF).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council on Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov said about the illegality of the closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the management of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that the revocation of the license would not happen.
The Rosbalt court showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be in the media in Russia today - a big question.
