The arsenal is believed to contain more than 1,000 tons of nerve agent, mustard gas, and other banned chemicals stored in dozens of different locations.
To destroy it, it is necessary that the OPCW and the Syrian authorities agree on a timetable of action for the first time, which is two weeks.
OPCW Field Operations Chief Jerry Smith told the BBC that his inspectors “were personally watching the destruction of the equipment.”
“They now have no opportunity to continue producing or mixing chemical weapons,” he said.
The OPCW statement said the inspectors visited 21 of the 23 facilities in Syria and made sure that the shell and poisonous substances factories were either destroyed or dismantled.
The remaining two facilities are too dangerous to carry out an inspection there, the document says, but the equipment from there was transported and inspected by OPCW experts.
According to Smith, the process of destroying the chemical weapons infrastructure was “particularly difficult” as work had to be done in the context of the ongoing conflict.
In early October, the OPCW won the Nobel Peace Prize, but Smith said the inspectors had not yet had time to celebrate – they were too busy with their work.
John Kerry says in his unprecedented admission that U.S. espionage “has gone unnecessarily far”
John Kerry has demonstrated a softening of U.S. surveillance program protection tactics by making an unprecedented admission that in some cases U.S. espionage has “gone unnecessarily far.”
The secretary of state also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being “on autopilot” during the appearance of Edward Snowden’s loud disclosures about NSA spying activities.
These leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic scandal with its allies.
Speaking on video at an open government conference in London, Mr. Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, actually perceived some of the things happening on autopilot because such an opportunity had already existed — both during World War II and in the very difficult years of the Cold War.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage went too far, but stressed that no one’s rights were violated.
He said: “In some cases it has gone inappropriately far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis so that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA had acted in good faith and that his surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow up people and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and killing people because we were able to learn about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint anti-terrorism efforts with the U.S., the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs chairman said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations due to disappointment over the surveillance carried out by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important for U.S. national security interests that Europeans remain our advocates for our common counter-terrorism efforts,” Murphy, who is serving as the first-term Democrat and chair of the Senate’s Subcommittee on International Relations on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
“And I’m going to Europe to let them know that we have to continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at these NSA programs.”
The news that the NSA had collected millions of records of phone calls in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of metadata collected by NATO allies and shared with the United States.
Other disclosures cited documents released by Snowden suggesting that the NSA was monitoring German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended espionage activities against the Allies as necessary and said it was a normal affair on both sides.
Against the background of this rumor, Murphy said that his office is organizing a trip of members of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes that the delegation will include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the travel program is still in the development stage.
While Murphy said the trip's goal was to help improve the relationship, he said a degree of "hardness from the best motives" would also be displayed.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people in what spyware they themselves have used for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also agree that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is due to head to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address the issues of hostility to the U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
