A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming to have been attacked by a taxi driver, filed an appeal and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by the Phuket Provincial Court of filing a false suit on June 15 following a Thai police report that a local taxi driver carried out the attack on the night of Sunday, June 10, while two other men detained her.
However, video surveillance footage later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after a breakup with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before she admitted to fabricating the story.
Before the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison term in a general-regime detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than a women's adult prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and was waiting for her return to Australia.
"Obviously it was an alarming time, but we hope that she will come home safely as soon as possible," Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail at 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the Krabi resort area in southern Thailand.
Thailand's legal sources said Bamford is currently representing a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to a court increase her sentence to two years and force her to serve an adult prison term.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, leading to an acquittal.
